# Public Talk — coordinator v2 (M5.3, pool entry 2 of 3).
#
# Speaker: elder_coordinator (cast.md § 4.1, Coordinator of Elders).
# Per-talk effects fire on [signal arg="TALK_COMPLETED"] via meeting_hall.gd
# → MeetingManager.resolve_talk_completed(&"public_talk", &"coordinator_pt_v2").
#
# Pool: this is one of three Public Talk speeches in
# MeetingManager.TALK_TYPE_TO_SPEECH_POOL[&"public_talk"]. Theme distinct
# from _v1 and _v3 (subagent picks per cast.md § 4.1 + Society-of-the-
# Truth theological frame in dialogue-context.md § 4). Register: warm-
# patriarchal, "you might consider," scripture-as-punctuation, the
# deliberate pause before hard application.
#
# Inner-voice gate (M5 Phase 1 Decision B): direct-read
# DoubtMeter.value >= 40 inline conditional. One italic line at a hand-
# authored beat between pages 2 and 3, landing as a private thought
# catching on something just said — not commentary on the speaker.

join elder_coordinator (neutral) at center

elder_coordinator (neutral): Good morning, brothers and sisters. Our theme this morning is one Paul wrote about at 2 Timothy 3 — that in the last days, critical times hard to deal with would be here. I think most of us, if we're honest, look at the news these days and feel that the apostle wasn't speaking only to his own century. He was speaking to ours.

elder_coordinator (neutral): I remember a brother in our circuit — many of you knew him, Brother Halloran — who used to say something I've never forgotten. He'd say, "I've been waiting for the New System my whole life, and you know what? The wait has been the gift." He meant that the waiting has shaped him. It taught him patience he didn't have at twenty. It taught him whose company is worth keeping. You'll find that the closer the day comes, the more the things of this system begin to feel — well, thin. Almost transparent.

if DoubtMeter.value >= 40:
	[i]Brother Halloran died last spring. He didn't see it.[/i]

elder_coordinator (neutral): So when you find yourself weary this week, brothers and sisters — and we all do — go back to the promise. The Great Tribulation is not the end of the story. It's the threshold. Jehovah has not forgotten one of us. As we read at Romans 8:25, if we hope for what we do not see, we keep on waiting for it with endurance. That endurance is yours. Have a blessed day.

[signal arg="TALK_COMPLETED"]
[end_timeline]
